Add the association state and a pure, testable resolver to `apps/desktop/src/stores/terminalStore.ts`.

### State
Add to `TerminalState`:
```ts
// issueNumber (as string) -> terminalId, per project. Session-only: NOT
// persisted, because partialize() regenerates every leaf's terminalId on
// reload, which would make persisted associations point at dead IDs.
terminalByWorkIdByProject: Record<string, Record<string, string>>;
```
Initialise to `{}` in `initialState`.

### Action
Add to `TerminalActions`:
```ts
associateWorkTerminal: (issueNumber: number, terminalId: string) => void;
```
Implementation mirrors the other actions — uses `getProjectId()`, immutably sets `terminalByWorkIdByProject[projectId][String(issueNumber)] = terminalId`.

### cleanupProject
Extend the existing `cleanupProject` to also drop the project's entry from `terminalByWorkIdByProject` (one destructure line, same as the other two maps).

### partialize
Do NOT add `terminalByWorkIdByProject` to the `partialize` return — associations are session-only by design (see the state comment above).

### Pure resolver helper (exported for testing)
```ts
// Resolves an issue's recorded terminal association to a *live* terminal.
// Returns null when there is no association OR the associated terminal no
// longer exists in any tab (closed split / removed tab) — the caller hides
// the Jump button in both cases ("gracefully hide when no association").
export function resolveWorkTerminal(
  workMap: Record<string, string> | undefined,
  tabs: TerminalTab[],
  issueNumber: number,
): { tabId: string; terminalId: string } | null {
  const terminalId = workMap?.[String(issueNumber)];
  if (!terminalId) return null;
  for (const tab of tabs) {
    if (getTerminalIds(tab.splitRoot).includes(terminalId)) {
      return { tabId: tab.id, terminalId };
    }
  }
  return null;
}
```
`getTerminalIds` is already imported from `./splitTree`.

### Test
New `apps/desktop/src/stores/terminalStore.test.ts` covering `resolveWorkTerminal`: (a) returns null when no association, (b) returns null when the associated terminalId isn't in any tab, (c) returns `{tabId, terminalId}` when the terminal is a live leaf — including a split-tree tab where the terminal is a non-root leaf. Use `createLeaf` / a hand-built `SplitNode` for fixtures.
